{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_froid_ver01/data/sn86075284/00517178706/1929112801/0965.xml":{"full_text":"POPLAB, MONTANA\n^oplat 9tattdacd\nAnd Continuation Of\nW Srocktnn Bulletin\nCARPENTER DELGER, PUBLISHERS\nTHE BEST IN NEWSPAPER JOB PRINTING SERVICE\nSubscription Price\u2014s2.oo Per Year\nEntered as second class matter on May 19, 1910, at the post\noffice at Poplar, Montana, under the Act of March 3, 1879\nWHO CAUSED THE CRASH?\n(From The Great Falls Tribune)\nAmong the many alibis offered in Wall Street for\nthe recent stock market debacle is the charge that\nthe western and southern senators precipitated the\ncrash through their refusal to support the tariff bill\nwhich had been prepared by the eastern industrial\nists.\nGranting, for the sake of argument, that psychol\nogy plays an important part in the stock market and\nthat stock fluctuations reflect, as a rule, the opinions\nof traders as to the business outlook, is it not a con\nfession of unreasonable selfishness to contend that\neastern business does not want agriculture and in\ndustry to attain an economic parity?\nA year ago, republican campaigners, some of\nthem with AV all Street connections, were assuring\nthe public that so long as the Fordney-McCumber\ntariff\u2014the law now in effect* \u2014remained unimpaired,\nbusiness would be good. This tariff was depicted as\nthe fount of all our material blessings, the cure for\nunemployment, the source of high wages, the bed\nrock of prosperity.\nSo the demand for higher industrial tariff rates\nat this time can be explained only in one of two\nways. Either there has been a great economic revo\nlution which has destroyed the effectiveness of our\npresent protective schedule, or industry is not sat\nisfied with the prosperity which it so lavishly ex\ntolled a few months ago.\nAll of us know there has been no profound econ\nomic revolution during the past year. Henee, we are\nforced to the conclusion that the demand for a high-\nINDIAN LAND SALE WHAT\u2019S THIS?\nOn November 23, 1929, there will be Ezra: What is a bigamist?\nheld a sale of 40 selected tracts of In- Cyrus: A man who mnkes the same\ndian land on the Fort Peck Reserva- mistake twice.\ntion. For particulars as to description,\nappraisements, terms of sale, etc., apply g oar j Bill\nto Superintendent, Fort Peck Agency, The \u2019board\" bill tor Inlmhltanta Of\nPoplar, Montana. 24-gt the Chicago zoo Is S2A.(HNi annually.\nBAZAAR and DINNER\nGiven By\nPresbyterian Ladies Aid\nSaturday, December 7th\nIn The Church Basement\nPlenty to Elat at Noon\nMany articles on Sale at Low Prices\nEvery Student Should Have\nAccess to a Typewriter\u2014\nAs an encouragement to more work, a\nmeans to better work, and training in a most\ndesirable accomplishment, a typewriter has\nno equal. Every home of children of school\nage should have a good machine constantly\nready for the student\u2019s use. Students of com\nmercial work have especial need.\nThe Royal Portable is the ideal machine for\nthe home. Sturdy, it will last a lifetime of school\nwork and personal and business correspond\nence of the parents. It can be purchased in any\nbeautiful colored finish. The cost is compara\ntively small. A payment plan is offered.\nPlan now to buy for the holidays. It will be\na present for every member of the family.\nTHE POPLAR STANDARD\ner tariff was prompted by selfishness. Conceding\nthat prices of stocks were bullish in anticipation of\nindustry getting a juicier slice of the tariff melon,\nshould the western and southern senators who block\ned this raid on the consumer\u2019s purse be blamed for\ndoing what was right, even if it brought a bearish\nreaction on the market?\nAre not the speculators who forced a bull mar-\nket, expecting the consuming public to sustain it, to\nbe condemned more than those who are earnestly\nstriving to keep business on a sound foundation?\n'Die Tribune believes that the recent orgy of\nspeculation was an annoying fester on legitimate\nbusiness and that it was a good thing for the country\nas a whole when it was lanced.\nIn the final analysis, responsibility for the crash\nrests witli those whose activities forced the price\nof stocks above the level justified by legitimate\nearnings.\nMORE HONESTY MOW\n(From Montana Record-Herald)\nA Pennsylvania storekeeper has been able to re\ntire after 35 years behind the counter because his\ncustomers in the last decade have been more prompt\nin paying their bills than were his customers during\nthe first 25 years. He says there are fewer deadbeats\nin 1929 than there were in 1892. How is this to be\nreconciled with those forlorn lamentations so often\nheard nowadays about the world going to the dogs,\nerime waves, loss of faith in humanity and many\nsimilar prophecies fearful to contemplate?\nAnd the people who pay their debts on the first\nof the month' do not all live in that one village and\ndon't all trade at that one general store. A national\nassociation of credit men has accumulated statistics\nshowing that 95 per eent of Americans pay their\nstore bills promptly, and of the other 5 per cent the\nmajority are slow but sure pay. Few of the millions\nof automobiles sold in this country every year are\nsold for cash, and yet the loss resulting from \u201cbad\ncredit is less than one-half of 1 per cent.\nFifty-one per cent of the retail business of this\ncountry is done on a credit basis, according to credit\nmen. The traditional 30 days\u2019 credit is still in wide\nspread use and the deferred or partial payment\nplan of buying is in universal use where large am\nounts are involved. Where there is so much credit\nthere must be trustworthy people.\nRUPTURE\nEXPERT HERE\nC. F. Redlieh, Minneapolis, Minn.,\nnationally famous Rupture Appliance\nExpert, will demonstrate without\ncharge his unequalled method at the\nGREAT NORTHERN HOTEL, WIL\nLISTON, MONDAY, DEO. 2, Hours 10-4\n4 and TUESDAY, DEO. 3, from 9-11\na. m.\nMr. C. F. Redlieh says:\nThe \u201cPerfect Retention Shields\u2019\u2019\nhold the rupture perfectly, no matter\nwhat position the body assumes or\nhow heavy a weight you lift. They\ngive instant relief and contract the\nopening in a remarkably short time.\nThe secret of their success is in\ntheir simplicity. An expertly adjusted\ndevice seals the opening without dis\ncomfort or detention from work. It is\npractically everlasting, sanitary, com\nfortable and actually holds the rup\ntures which heretofore were considered\nuncontrollable.\n\u201cIF YOU WANT TO HAVE IT\nDONE RIGHT\u2014-BEE REDUCE.\u201d\nDoctor J. W. Seaver, for many years\nin charge of the Physical Education of\nthe students of Yale College, hns re\ncorded 75% cures with this system.\nMr. Redlieh is internationally known\nand speaks English, German and Span\nish.\nHOME OFFICE:\n535 Boston Block, Minneapolis, Winn\nAdv.\u2014ltp\nTHE POPLAB STANDABD\nIn the District Court of the Twentieth\nJudicial District of the State of Mon\ntana, in and for the County of Roose\nvelt.\nWESTERN LOAN AND BUILDING\nCOMPANY, a corporation, Plaintiff,\nvs.\nJ. B. SWITZER, and MI LIAN SWIT\nZER, his wife; FIRST NATIONAL\nBANK, a corporation: ROOSEVELT\nCOUNTY, a body politic and corporate,\nand FIRST STATE BANK, a corpora\ntion. Defendants.\nNOTICE OF SHERIFF'S BALE\nTO BE SOLD AT SHERIFF\u2019S SALE,\nat the front door of the courthouse at\nWolf Point, Roosevelt County, Mon\ntana, on the 30th day of November,\n1929, at the hour of two o'clock P. M.\nof said day, the following described\nproperty, to-wit:\nAll that certain piece, parcel ot\nland situate, lying and being in the\nCounty of Roosevelt, State of Mon\ntana, and more particularly des\ncribed as Lot One <1) of Block\nFourteen (14), of the original\nTownsite of Wolf Point, Montana.\nDated this sth dav of November,\n1929.\nJ. H. ANDERSON,\nSheriff.\nBy ARCHIE COUNCIL,\nDeputy Sheriff.\nTHOMAS DIGNAN, Plaintiff\u2019s Attor\nney, Glasgow, Montana. 29-4 t\nNOTICE FOR PUBLICATION\nDepartment ot the Interior, U. S.\nLand Office at Great Falls, Montana,\nNovember 5, 1929.\nNOTICE is hereby given that\nBEN W. NORDWICK\nof Dowd. Montana, who. on December\n13, 1924, made Homestead, Act. 2-\n19-1909, No. 058815, for South half,\nSection 33, Township 32 North, Rango\n51 East, Principal Meridian, has filed\nnotice of intention to make Five year\nProof, to establish claim to the land\nabove described, before George B. Ban\nta, U. S. Commissioner, at Poplar, Mon\ntana, on the 16th dav of December,\n1929.\nClaimant names as witnesses:\nArvid Pohl, of Dowd. Mont.,\nRobert Pohl, of Dowd. Mont.,\nA. L. Nordwick, of Dowd, Mont.,\nO. L. Nordwick, of Dowd, Mont.\nM. D. NICHOLSON,\n(Ist pub. 11-14 last 12-12) Register.\nA LUCEY STRIKE\nA colored preacher said to his cong\nregation: \u201cThere\u2019s a certain man am\nong us who is flirting with another\nman's wife. Unless he puts five dollars\niu the collection box his name will be\nread from the pulpit.\u201d\nWhen the box came in there were\nninteen five-dollar hills in it and a\ntwo-dollar bill with a note pinned to\nit, saying: \u201cThis is all the cash I\nhave, but will send the other three\ndollars Wednesday.\u201d\nBusiness and\nProfessional\nDirectory\n\nB. M. MOBFOBD t\nAttoroey-et-Lew X\nPoplar Montana T\nofmiiiiiiiniiiiiiiiif\nDB. 0. A. BWAITMX\ni Phydcian and Burgoon\nOfflec Houn: 10 to 11; 1:10 to 4\nTalephono 1\nOfleo 101; Beddene, 70\nPoplar, Montana\n1 BUCK MOUM\nAttonop-at-law\nPort Ofleo Building\nPoplar, Montana\n\n111 I IISOOIIIIIIIIIII^O\nJ Office Phone 90; Beaidenee SO\nDB. O. W. WZPBUD\nDentlrt\nOfleo. Over Poot Ofleo\nPoplar, Montana\nmoiiomiiooiiiiiiiiiiim\n^\u2666IIIIIIHHIIIIIIHIIIM^\nW. L. 8088\nAttorney-aMn*\nPractice in AH Court.\nPoplar, Montana\nMH Illi HOO Illi f 1111 ml\nyiIIIIIMIIMIIIIHIM\nCITY SKOB MOBFITAXi\nDtTid J. Dnproo, Prop.\nAgent Aladdin Lamp.\nPoplar, Mantana\n\u2022\u2666\u2666mu i leeooooMMiieoi\n\nABT MOXB\n\u25a0lootrio PpUttMM BBS X\nGeneral Wiring\nDeleo Light Gyatoau\nPoplar, Montana\nAndersin Community\nMm. Otcur Qualley will entertain\nthe Zion Lutheran Ladies Aid at her\nhome Saturday, the 7th of December,\n.\u2022it one o\u2019clock.\nMr. and Mrs. Jake Lauridsen made a\nbusinees trip to Wolf Point Monday.\nMiss Anna Hartkopf, Lawrence Lar*\nson and Lillian and Norman Knoblock\nwere guests at the Oscar Dahlberg\nhome Sunday.\nMn. Jim Craigie entertained the\nZion Lutheran Ladies Aid at the church\nbasement Wednesday. A business meet\ning was held and the new officers elect\ned were Mrs. Jake Lauridsen, presid\nent; Mrs. John Reum, vice president;\nMrs. Vic Johnson, secretary; and Mrs.\nE. C. Larson, treasurer.\nMr. and Mrs. Oscar Dahlberg were\nbusiness callers in Poplar Tuesday.\nOscar Qualley and Henry Lauridscn\nwere business callers in Poplar Monday.\nMrs. Christine Lauridsen and daught\ner Alice, called at the Oscar Dahlberg.\nAnna Hartkopf, and Jake Lauridsen\nhomes Monday.\nOscar and Henry Lauridsen and\nMisses Mila Atkins and Lucy McKee\nwere guests at the Oscar Qualley home\nSaturday evening and Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Oscar Dahlberg and\ndaughter Doris, are leaving Wednesday\nthis week for Minnesota where they\nwill spend the winter visiting friends\nand relatives.\nGordon Rodewald shot a coyote Mon\nday. This is his second one in a week.\nMelvin Qualley called at the Oscar\nQualley home Monday.\nMr. and Mrs. Jake Lauridsen and\nMrs. P. Lauridsen called at the L. C.\nLauridsen home.\nNew Coal Mine\n7 Mills East IMili North\nof Brockton\nGood Measure No Clinkers\nCharley Creek News\nJakte Frizier and family moved onto\nthe Nicholson place thia week. Mrs.\nNicholson is leaving for St. Paul for\nan extended visit with her sister, Mrs.\nMinser.\nGeorge Fisher was quite seriously\nhurt Monday while riding after cattle.\nHis horse slipped and fell while running\nfast. The fall stunned him so that he\nwas partially unconscious for several\ndays. His face is badly bruised and\nskinned and the flesh between his lower\nlip and jawbone is torn loose so that\nthe roots of several of his lower front\nteeth are exposed.\nMiss Esther Sehlenz spent Wednes\nday night with Stella Fisher.\nMr. and Mrs. Wm. M. Ralston and\nJohn Sylverknub spent Wednesday ev\nening at the Fisher home.\nAndy Sehlenz is doing quite n lot of\nbusiness at the mine this weels as ev\neryone seems to be getting ready for a\ncold snap.\nRoy Gibbs sold a milk cow to Chas.\nSterling Tuesday.\nRalph Hagen and William Fehrs\nwere Sunday evening callers at the\nFisher home.\nWE WANT TO MAKE OUR\nNEW YEAR HAPPY\nWe would like to close our books\non December 31 without a single\nAccount Unpaid.\nC\u2019mon Give Us a Lift\nSend in that Check!\nWo want you to know wo really do appreciate the\nbusiness you have given us and that wo do not ob\nject to carrying responsible people on our books for\na reasonable length of time. Wo believe, too, you ap\npreciate our giving you credit. Wow wo are asking\nyou to show your appreciation by paying your ac\ncount by the end of the year. It will bo just as easy\nto pay it now as in January or February\u2014perhaps\neasier. And it will bo Just as easy to send a chock\ntoday as it would bo next wook. Give us a lift!\nGrogan-Robinson Lumber Co.\nDrew School Report\nMonth of November\nBoys enrolled, 18; girls, 18; total en\nrollment, 36. Per cent of attendance,\n97. Perfect attendance: Mario Jones,\nRachel Counter, Rosaline Jones, Ursula\nBlack Dog, Vina Spotted Bull, Norman\nHallow, Fannie Lone Dog, Mathew\nBlack Dog, Allen Spotted Bull, James\nBlack Dog,\nBest scholarship: First grade, Joseph\nHauling of All Kinds\nDraying Transfer Work\nAgent Continental Oil Co.\nROY F. SPARKS\nFARMERS ELEVATOR CO.\n\u201cA HOME INSTITUTION\u201d\nWholesale Dealers In\nWhite Eagle Gasoline and\nSunoco Oils\nDelivery of these Products can be made\nto your Farm at the regular charge.\nDrums Furnished Free of Charge.\nWe Sell For Cash Only.\nComa in and have your claims for refund on Gas Tax Won it to\nontlawed.\nFarmers Elevator Co.\nBrocktoo, Mellon\nC. J. Samuelson, Manager\nCHAS. A. PRIOR, President JOB RUFF ATTO, Vice Pim.\nH. G. DRUBSEPOW, Secretary\nBAILEY nSHBR PBDBB MOB\nTHURS., NOV. M, 19#.\nLamber; second grade, Lavinia Lone\nDog; third grade, Norman Hallow;\nfourth grade: Mary Perry, fifth grade,\nAnton Hallow. Visitors: 12.\nSpecial work this -month: the Pil\ngrims, causes for Thanksgiving, comp\nosition and memory work nnd prepara\ntion for the Thanksgiving program.\nSophia A. Anderson, tencher.","height":"22720","width":"18276"}}
